<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="361" type="type material">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="361">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="361">Holotype and paratype: ANSP A7028, 2 specimens (one whole except for removal of buccal mass, measuring 45.8 mm long preserved and the other dissected, measuring 46.7 mm long preserved); ANSP 187712, 1 shell (18.7 mm) and gizzard plates of dissected specimen of A7028 (H. A. Pilsbry coll., iv/1951), 1 slide with radulas of dissected specimens.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="361" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="361">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Aplysiidae" genus="Aplysia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aplysia badistes" order="Aplysiida" pageId="0" pageNumber="361" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="badistes">Aplysia badistes</taxonomicName>
Pilsbry, 1951 is the type species of 
<taxonomicName infraspecific-rank="subgenus" lsidName="(Metaplysia)" pageId="0" pageNumber="361" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Metaplysia">subgenus Metaplysia</taxonomicName>
Pilsbry, 1951. Pilsbry stated &quot;Type and another specimen are 187712 ANSP&quot;. Pilsbry described the internal anatomy from one specimen but extracted the radula from both. Someone separated the shell and gizzard plates as ANSP 188279, and labeled them 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Paratype”">&quot;Paratype&quot;</normalizedToken>
, a term not used in the publication. We have restored them to the original catalogue number (187712) as it is not possible to tell which specimen Pilsbry intended to be the holotype.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
